Like others point out, this location doesn't take credit cards at the register. I wish I had known this before going in. It is not true to say they are cash only, though. They accept a few Chinese e-commerce payment systems, such as AliPay, their official app (the minimum load is a very steep $25), and Venmo, which I set up an account for the sole purpose of paying here. I quickly found a seat and languished with my phone for what seemed like 15 minutes going through these alternative payment methods until finding one that worked for me. By then, a long line formed, but since I sat down it was thankfully one I did not happen to hold up.  It sounds incredibly petty of an online reviewer to deduct a star for a restaurant being anti-card, but I insist upon such pettiness, on account of the inconveniences it presents so many of Kung Fu Tea's first time customers. I had no cash and their WiFi to download their app and Venmo was slow as molasses.  The atmosphere is cafe-like, though I did not linger long after obtaining my drink. It seems friendly enough to stay a little while.  Regarding the drink I had, it was deliciousness incarnate. I had an Oreo slush that was out of this world... seriously! I think when I have cash or enough money to pay via Venmo I'll come back. My hope long-term is they consider getting a Clover or Square payment solution. Credit and debit card processing fees are not as high as they used to be; with the money this place is making they can certainly be making far more by taking plastic and contactless payments.  If you’re getting the Oreo drink, be sure to try the Slush and not the WOW Milk. They’re very different drinks.
